00:04:10.390 --> 00:04:18.100
In 1998, in a small town in India, a man was tired of seeing his wife's struggle with the inconveniences of the female menstrual cycle.

55
00:04:19.070 --> 00:04:25.220
His wife was collecting filthy rags and newspapers to use as sanitary pads while she was on her period

56
00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:28.890
Because the pads that were made by multinational corporations were just too expensive.

57
00:04:29.930 --> 00:04:35.090
So he decided to start experimenting to see if he could create a more cost-effective option for the women in this country.

58
00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:41.080
He tried different materials, sizes, and chemicals, but his wife and sisters didn't like any of them.

59
00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:48.270
He becomes so obsessed with this idea that his wife and sisters eventually refuse to be test subjects for his project.

60
00:04:49.170 --> 00:04:54.460
So he looked for other women to test his invention, but they weren't even open to talking about their menstrual cycles with him

61
00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:57.700
As they were kind of shy and it was like a taboo topic at the time.

62
00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:02.900
But instead of giving up, he started testing the sanitary pads on himself.

63
00:05:04.030 --> 00:05:10.610
This man would fill a bladder with animal blood to simulate a woman menstruating just so he could test his invention.

64
00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:17.250
And this quickly made him the laughing stock of the village and his family and friends thought he was fucking crazy and they began to ostracize him.

65
00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:21.630
He started giving his products to girls at the local medical college for free

66
00:05:21.950 --> 00:05:25.650
Just to get some feedback from the people who would actually use the product.

67
00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:33.120
It took him over two years to finally find the right materials and invent a low-cost machine

68
00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:38.110
That could produce the sanitary pads the right way at a price that women in India could afford.

69
00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:45.150
Eventually, he went on to have his invention recognized nationally and even got financial investments to scale his company.

70
00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:51.070
And now he's praised as a man who played a major role in changing women's lives forever in India.

71
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:56.560
The pad-making machine that he invented also creates jobs and income for many women,

72
00:05:56.850 --> 00:06:02.160
And the affordable pads enable a lot more women to continue working and making money while they're on their period.

73
00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:09.190
So this man has undoubtedly inspired people all over his country to do great things like start businesses,

74
00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:12.010
Create solutions to other social issues in their country.

75
00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:17.740
Stay dedicated to your purpose and to never give up just because it gets difficult or people think you're crazy.

76
00:06:19.340 --> 00:06:25.110
There's no way that we can measure how much of a positive impact this man has had on his country and his people.

77
00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:35.460
So, was this man's decision to create a more cost-effective sanitary pad for his wife and sisters a good one or a bad one?

78
00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:40.660
It's our perspective that determines whether something is good or bad,

79
00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:46.670
And our perspective can change over time, which in turn can change how we look at a situation over time.

80
00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:50.660
What's good today, could be bad next year.

81
00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:59.410
But the reality is that things are neither good nor bad. They just are.